text: Sure. But I think that already classification and regression trees and neural networks were already pretty popular in those days when I applied machine learning to finance back in the 90s. These two techniques were widely known and widely practiced. But the main thing, from what I recall, the main problem, the main challenge that me and as well as other practitioners faced at that time was overfitting. It's very easy to get excellent back-test results using neural network or random force. Well, actually, random force wasn't quite involved at the time. So, this entry was much more the tool of the trade. So, they never really produced real profits. So, many people were disillusioned by machine learning over the next 10, 20 years because of this problem. Force positives was the main problem. And because of that, I myself have... I pretty much put the machine learning on the eyes starting in 2006 when I traded for myself because I certainly didn't want to generate force positives for my own trading. It's okay to generate force positives for your boss because you get paid a salary anyway. But when your own money is at stake, it is quite a different question. So, I practically abandoned machine learning for the next 10 years in my own trading, finding simple strategies, very classical quant techniques, statistical arbitrage. Co-integrating, co-integration, what have you. And just stick to low-dimensional space, low-parameters model for the longest time until a few years ago when we observed alpha decay on many simple models, including the ones that we traded. The proliferation of quant books and blogs and forums and podcasts pretty much democratize quant trading. And I might have contributed to part of it to my own alpha decay. So I figured that, well, what is the best way to recapture some of these uniqueness of strategies? Everybody knows about factors, momentum, mean reversion. What is the secret sauce anymore? And I thought that maybe machine learning will come back to help us. And now that we know about all these new advanced improvements to solve the overfitting problem, an example would be like in the field of neural networks. Since Professor Hinton developed the dropout technique to apply to deep learning, the issue of overfitting in neural network has been greatly reduced because of that major breakthrough, making it practical for many applications. So we decided to take another look at it about two years ago. Things were founded to make it work actually in practical trading, and we applied it to our KOH strategy with some success. So that's the problem. That's my journey with machine learning.
